<h2>Example slide code</h2>

<p>
Each slide is defined as a section element. Each have a specific duration i milliseconds (be careful).
</p>

<p> The CSS class <code>pictureCollection</code> and <code>eventCollection</code> are special classes used to
identify that a slide is supposed to be controlled by a javascript module. The <code>eventCollection</code> class
follows a specific format defined in <a href="{{ asset('bundles/dakinfoscreen/mods/eventCollection/eventCollection.js') }}">{{ asset('bundles/dakinfoscreen/mods/eventCollection/eventCollection.js') }}</a>.
</p>

<p><code>eventCollection</code> sections can be generated by adding a <code>&lt;div class="eventSlideTrigger" &gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code> to your slideshow.

You can also add several filtering arguments, each argument prefixed by <code>data-</code>, f.ex: <code>&lt;div class="eventSlideTrigger" data-dayspan="6"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;div class="eventSlideTrigger" data-dayspan="6" data-arranger="1"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code>. 

You can use the filters <code>dayspan</code>, <code>arranger</code>, <code>location</code>, <code>category</code> and <code>festival</code>.
You can specify multiple <code>arranger</code>, <code>location</code> and <code>category</code> by formatting as f.ex: <code>data-arranger="1,5"</code> or <code>data-location="12,2,4,6"</code>.
</p>

<pre>{% filter escape %}

<section data-duration="1000">
  <h1>This should only last 1 second</h1>
</section>
 
<section class="pictureCollection">
  <img src="http://placekitten.com/800/600" />
  <img src="http://placekitten.com/800/500" />
</section>

<div class="eventSlideTrigger" data-dayspan="2" display="display: none"></div>

<section>
  <h1>Some event by an arranger with id 1</h1>
</section>

<div class="eventSlideTrigger" data-arranger="1" display="display: none"></div>

<section data-duration="700">
  <h1>This should only last 700 milli seconds</h1>
</section>
{% endfilter %}
</pre>
